Restful auth - slightly better (#879)

* Remove unneeded comment

* Add authentication service which communicates with our specified
endpoint

- Use restApiClient instead of axios

* Expose authService via services/index

* Use authService in actions/users to communicate with /sessions endpoint

- Modify /login endpoint to be POST /sessions for a more restful API
- Instead of authenticating a user, we are asking our server to create
a session as a resource. We then UPDATE or DELETE this resource we are
creating.

* Simplify login method in user controller to return just a 200

- Any messaging can be defined on the client side (unless it's a server
related issue). This decouples our client and server further (the UI
previously had to understand the structure of the json response
returned). :) Context can be inferred through the HTTP status code
returned.
- Fix tests using stubs for login
- Move test to __tests__ folder

* Use authService in actions/users to communicate with /users endpoint

- Modify /signup endpoint to be POST /users for a more restful API

* Add signup method to authService

- Abstract the need of knowing what axios/restApiClient is. Instead use
  authService for its intended purpose for signup

* Simplify signup controller to just return status code without json

* Add logout method to authService

* Use authService in actions/users to logout

- Modify controllers to work with /sessions endpoint

* Remove unneeded exported functions in user action creator

* Remove unneeded variables in user test
